@gmpolice @manchesterfire @EnvAgency @metoffice 📊 Third is the table of weekly Pillar 2 testing figures per 100,000 people, up to Saturday 16 January.

🗣️ “This slide reflects increased levels of testing across Greater Manchester” says Andy, including with support from the military.

👇 https://t.co/2iVPhbWahj

@gmpolice @manchesterfire @EnvAgency @metoffice 📊 The second slide is the ‘heat map’ comparison of age-specific case rates across Greater Manchester.

🗣️ “It’s there for all age groups”, says Andy, “but particularly so with regard to the younger age range.”

👇 https://t.co/if3QcFWgAk

@gmpolice @manchesterfire @EnvAgency @metoffice 📊 Andy now turns to our regular #COVID19 updates, beginning with the 7-day rate of positive tests per 100,000 people to 15 January.

🗣️ “What this shows is a decrease overall for Greater Manchester over the last week”, he says, with all boroughs recording a small decrease.

👇 https://t.co/uHKiFWZ7sS

@gmpolice @manchesterfire @EnvAgency @metoffice 🗣️ “If people need to leave their property to protect themselves, their family, or their property, they are able to do so”, says Andy.

“People do need to know that they can take that action to protect themselves."

👇 https://t.co/BayH9fs45C

@gmpolice @manchesterfire @EnvAgency @metoffice 🗣️ “We remain alert to what is a very dynamic situation" says @manchesterfire CFO Dave Russel.

Incidents attended by crews today have involved people trapped in vehicles while trying to pass through flooded roads.

🗣️ "Don’t make any journeys unless it’s absolutely necessary."

@gmpolice @manchesterfire @EnvAgency @metoffice ⚠️ Flood warnings are in place for parts of our city-region.

If flooding has been forecast in your area, you can call Floodline on 0345 988 1188 or 0845 988 1188, or contact your local authority.

📲 To get flood warnings by phone, email or text, visit https://t.co/ayYZGLlTvl https://t.co/yEgU3ASoMo
